[normal]Nosheen’s[bold] case[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Nosheen
[normal] came to the 
[normal]UK
[normal] on a spousal visa in 2006 to join her British national husband 
[normal]and in-laws 
[normal]following an arranged marriage in 
[normal]Pakistan
[normal]. From the outset of her marriage, she was repeated
[normal]ly
[normal] abuse
[normal]d, imprisoned and 
[normal]forced to conceive. She 
[normal]was 
[normal]forbidden from having contact with her family in 
[normal]Pakistan
[normal] 
[normal]or
[normal] relatives in the 
[normal]UK
[normal].
[normal] She was 
[normal]n
[normal]ot allowed 
[normal]to atte
[normal]nd her GP surgery 
[normal]unless accompanied by her mother-in-law. 
[normal]She therefore had little opportunity to 
[normal]fully 
[normal]disclose her experiences
[normal] of abuse and imprisonment
[normal] 
[normal]to outsi
[normal]de agencies. 
[normal]H
[normal]er family 
[normal]and relatives
[normal] to whom she had disclosed her experiences,
[normal] told her t
[normal]o
[normal] ‘adjust’ to her new surroundings and to make her marriage work. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Within 7 months of her arrival in the 
[normal]UK
[normal], 
[normal]Nosheen
[normal] was found set alight in her garden. She was taken to hospital 
[normal]having 
[normal]sustained 60% burns. 
[normal]Nosheen
[normal] was responding well to treatment and at 
[normal]t
[normal]he first opportunity
[normal] she had
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]she
[normal] told the hospital that she did not want her husband or in-laws to visit her.
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he hospital did not act on her wishes and instead allowed her husband and in-laws unrestricted and unsupervised access to her. Following one of 
[normal]their visits, she 
[normal]suffered catastrophic brain injury
[normal]. The
[normal] 
[normal]oxygen ventilator
[normal] 
[normal]to which
[normal] she was connected, inexplicably 
[normal]be
[normal]c
[normal]a
[normal]me
[normal] dislodged. As a result of her brain injuries, she is now cortically blind, minimally conscious and needs 24 hour care. Her condition
[normal] is life-long.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In this condition, the UKBA tried to deport her. She was appointed an official solicitor
[normal] and an immigration lawyer
[normal] 
[normal]as she could not give instructions. 
[normal]The decision to deport her was challenged
[normal] on medical grounds
[normal] at an appeal tribunal. C
[normal]onsi
[normal]derable medical evidence was presented to 
[normal]show that 
[normal]she 
[normal]would not 
[normal]surviv
[normal]e
[normal] the plane journey and even if she did, 
[normal]she would not 
[normal]receive the specialised
[normal] medical
[normal] care she needed in Pakistan. She won her appeal.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]D
[normal]espite her horrific
[normal] injuries,
[normal] to dat
[normal]e, there 
[normal]has been no effective S
[normal]tate investigation into how she came to suffer serious harm at her home or at the hospital. 
[normal]The police undertook a
[normal] 
[normal]very superficial investigation 
[normal]based on an initial suspicion that she was 
[normal]the 
[normal]victim of an 
[normal]honour crime
[normal], although they
[normal] failed to warn the hospital authorities about their suspicions. 
[normal]Following her brain injury, 
[normal]the police suspended all investigations. 
[normal]The hospital too failed to undertake any investigation into how 
[normal]Nosheen
[normal] came to suffer her brain injury. 
[normal]Nosheen’s
[normal] father 
[normal]has been left without any explanation as to why there has been 
[normal]no state scrutiny to bear on the matter
[normal]. He 
[normal]visits 
[normal]Nosheen
[normal] on a daily basis
[normal] at 
[normal]a
[normal] nursing home
[normal] where she resides in a near vegetative state.
[normal]&#xa0;
