[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Dorothy[bold]’s case [bold]&#xa0;[bold]In November 2008, 
[normal]Dorothy
[normal], a Nigerian National, arrived in the UK on a vi
[normal]sitor’s visa
[normal] to join her 
[normal]husband
[normal],
[normal] a British National
[normal]. 
[normal]Her two children were born in the UK.
[normal] Followi
[normal]ng the birth of her second child, 
[normal]her husband 
[normal]began to 
[normal]abus
[normal]e
[normal] her
[normal] and assault 
[normal]her on almost
[normal] daily basis. 
[normal]I
[normal]n February 2013, he abandoned her 
[normal]and the
[normal] children. This was the second occasion that he had abandoned her 
[normal]but she remained hopeful that he would 
[normal]return
[normal].
[normal] After a couple of weeks, 
[normal]Dorothy
[normal] 
[normal]ran
[normal] out of money 
[normal]and food. She was
[normal] breastfeeding her second child
[normal] at the time
[normal]. She turned to social services f
[normal]or help and they agreed to assist her for 28 days. 
[normal]Dorothy also
[normal] tried to
[normal] obtain
[normal] immigration advice 
[normal]when 
[normal]she realised that her husband had done nothing 
[normal]to regularise her stay in the UK. He
[normal] had also taken the children’s British passports with him when he lef
[normal]t. 
[normal]However, as she had no documentation regarding her immigration status, she was unable to resolve her immigration problems within the 28 days. 
[normal]At the end of the 28 day period, social services cut off 
[normal]her
[normal] support and accused 
[normal]Dorothy of not sorting out her
[normal] immigration matter
[normal]. 
[normal]The told her that they would take the children into care. Dorothy
[normal] became homeless. 
[normal]She
[normal] 
[normal]instructed 
[normal]a 
[normal]community care solicitor
[normal] to act for her and 
[normal]SBS 
[normal]assisted her for a limited period 
[normal]through our ‘
[normal]No Recourse Fund
[normal]. This is
[normal] an emergency
[normal] f
[normal]und operated by SBS to help abused, destitute and homeless women with insecure status
[normal]. 
[normal]Dorothy
[normal]’s solicitor
[normal] 
[normal]successfully challenged social services’
[normal] decision on the basis that it was unlawful to terminate support to her and her children
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
