[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Mwahasi[bold]’ case[bold] [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Mwahasi
[normal], an Ethiopian National, was forced t
[normal]o marry her husband when she was 16 years old. In August 2012, 
[normal]Mwahasi
[normal] joined her husband in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] on a ‘post-flight’ spouse visa. This means that she 
[normal]could 
[normal]apply for settled status at a later date. Within a few days of her arrival in the 
[normal]UK
[normal], 
[normal]she was subj
[normal]ected to repeated domestic and sexual violence by her husband
[normal]. He
[normal] 
[normal]took 
[normal]her
[normal] earnings and often 
[normal]threatened to send her back to Ethiopia
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mwahasi
[normal] felt trapped in her marriage and started self- harming. She 
[normal]feared 
[normal]returning to 
[normal]Ethiopia
[normal] as a disgraced woman
[normal].
[normal] By February 2013, 
[normal]Mwahasi’s
[normal] husband’s behaviour deteriorated to such an extent that she had no choice but to call the police. 
[normal]She was taken to 
[normal]a night shelter but her immigration status prevented her
[normal] from claiming welfare benefits.
[normal] SBS assisted 
[normal]Mwahasi
[normal] in
[normal] finding temporary accommodation from a charit
[normal]able
[normal] organisation and in submitting an application for the DDV Concession
[normal], made on the basis that she had been
[normal] treated by the immigration authorities as a spousal visa applicant. 
[normal]Her application 
[normal]was refused. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I
[normal]n April 2013
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]Mwahasi
[normal]’s
[normal] 
[normal]immigration solicitor
[normal] 
[normal]challenge
[normal]d
[normal] the UKBA’s 
[normal]refusal
[normal] by way of judicial review. The case is currently pending at the High Court
[normal] 
[normal]which has decided that her 
[normal]case
[normal] raises an important public interest matte
[normal]r
[normal] relating to the proper remit of the DDV Concession. In the meantime, she has been given temporary leave to remain by the UKBA, which allows her recourse to public funds. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]L
[normal]egal Aid Agency also refused 
[normal]Mwahasi
[normal]’s
[normal] applicati
[normal]on for exceptional case fundin
[normal]g 
[normal]to 
[normal]make an application for indefinite leave to remain in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] under the DV Rule
[normal]. She was told that 
[normal]it would only be granted if there was a successful outcome of the judicial review proceedings
[normal] in respect of
[normal] the DDV Concession. 
